NOTES_1PETER = {
    1: {
        1: 'GREEK: "Parepidēmois" (παρεπιδήμοις, Strong\'s G3927) denotes resident aliens or temporary sojourners — those dwelling alongside but not belonging to the native population. "Diaspora" (διασπορά, G1290) originally referred to Jews scattered among Gentile nations; Peter applies this theologically to the Church as the new covenant community dispersed in the world. HISTORICAL: The five Roman provinces listed cover most of Asia Minor (modern Turkey), suggesting a circular letter route.',
        2: 'THEOLOGICAL: The Trinitarian structure here is striking — election grounded in the foreknowledge of God the Father, effected in the sanctification of the Spirit, directed toward obedience and the sprinkling of the blood of Jesus Christ. TYPOLOGY: "Rhantismon" (ῥαντισμόν, G4473) recalls the covenant sprinkling of blood in Exodus 24:7-8 and the purification rites of Numbers 19, typologically fulfilled in Christ\'s atoning blood.',
        3: 'GREEK: "Anagennēsas" (ἀναγεννήσας, G313) — "having begotten again" — is rare in the NT, appearing only here and in 1:23. It conveys divine causation of new birth, not mere moral renewal. TYPOLOGY: "Living hope" (elpída zōsan) stands in contrast to dead hopes of the old age; the resurrection of Christ is the ground and guarantee of this hope (cf. 1 Cor 15:17-20).',
        5: 'GREEK: "Phrouroumenous" (φρουρουμένους, G5432) is a military term meaning "garrisoned" or "guarded," depicting believers as a city kept under divine protection. THEOLOGICAL: The tension between divine sovereignty ("by the power of God") and human responsibility ("through faith") is held together without resolution — both are simultaneously operative in the preservation of the saints.',
        7: 'GREEK: "Dokimion" (δοκίμιον, G1383) refers to the tested and proven quality of faith, not the testing process itself. The term was used in metallurgy for assayed metals. TYPOLOGY: The refining of gold through fire as a metaphor for tested faith echoes Malachi 3:2-3 and Zechariah 13:9, where God refines His people as silver and gold. The goal is eschatological vindication at the "apokalypsis" (ἀποκαλύψει) — the unveiling of Jesus Christ.',
        11: 'THEOLOGICAL: "The Spirit of Christ in them" (τὸ ἐν αὐτοῖς πνεῦμα Χριστοῦ) identifies the Spirit who inspired the OT prophets as the Spirit of the pre-incarnate Christ, affirming Christ\'s active role in redemptive history prior to the incarnation. GREEK: "Promartyromenon" (προμαρτυρόμενον, G4303) is a hapax legomenon in the NT, meaning "testifying beforehand." TYPOLOGY: The dual testimony — sufferings (pathēmata) followed by glories (doxas) — establishes the prophetic pattern fulfilled in Christ\'s passion and exaltation (cf. Luke 24:26-27, Isa 53).',
        12: 'DIVINE_COUNCIL: The remarkable closing phrase — "into which things angels desire to look" (εἰς ἃ ἐπιθυμοῦσιν ἄγγελοι παρακύψαι) — reveals that the unfolding mystery of salvation through Christ is an object of intense interest even to the heavenly host. "Parakýpsai" (G3879) means to stoop down and peer intently, as one bending to examine something closely. This echoes the divine council theme: the angelic beings observe God\'s redemptive plan with wonder (cf. Eph 3:10).',
        16: 'TYPOLOGY: Peter quotes Leviticus 11:44-45 and 19:2 from the LXX. The holiness command given to Israel at Sinai is now applied directly to the new covenant community, affirming continuity between God\'s purposes for Israel and the Church. The imperative "you shall be holy" (ἅγιοι ἔσεσθε) is grounded in the indicative character of God: "for I am holy."',
        19: 'TYPOLOGY: "As of a lamb without blemish and without spot" (ὡς ἀμνοῦ ἀμώμου καὶ ἀσπίλου) directly evokes the Passover lamb of Exodus 12:5 and the Suffering Servant of Isaiah 53:7. "Amōmos" (G299) and "aspilos" (G784) are sacrificial-technical terms requiring physical perfection in Temple offerings, applied here to the moral perfection of Christ. THEOLOGICAL: The redemption is not merely moral example but substitutionary purchase — "elytrōthēte" (ἐλυτρώθητε, G3084) is the language of ransom and manumission from slavery.',
        20: 'THEOLOGICAL: "Foreknown before the foundation of the world" (προεγνωσμένου πρὸ καταβολῆς κόσμου) places Christ\'s redemptive role in the eternal counsel of God, prior to creation itself. "Katabolē kosmou" (G2602 + G2889) — "the laying down of the world" — indicates that the cross was not an emergency measure but the predetermined plan of God (cf. Acts 2:23, Rev 13:8). The contrast between hidden purpose ("foreknown") and historical manifestation ("made manifest at the last of the times") structures all of redemptive history.',
        23: 'GREEK: "Anagegennēmenoi" (ἀναγεγεννημένοι) — perfect passive participle of "anagennáō" (G313), indicating a completed divine action with ongoing results: "having been begotten again." THEOLOGICAL: The contrast between corruptible (phthartēs) and incorruptible (aphthartou) seed establishes that the new birth originates not in any perishable human agency but in the imperishable "logos" (λόγος) of God — His living and abiding word, which is both the instrument and sustaining power of regeneration (cf. Jas 1:18, John 1:12-13).',
    },
    2: {
        2: 'GREEK: "Artigennēta" (ἀρτιγέννητα, Strong\'s G738) is a rare compound meaning "just now born" or "newly begotten," appearing only here in the NT. "Logikon" (λογικόν, G3050) means "rational" or "pertaining to the word/logos," creating a wordplay—the "milk" is connected to the divine Logos. "Adolon" (ἄδολον, G97) means "without deceit/unadulterated," contrasting with the "dolos" (deceit) to be put off in v.1.',
        3: 'TYPOLOGY: Peter quotes Psalm 34:8 (LXX 33:9), "Taste and see that the Lord is good." The Greek "chrēstos" (χρηστός, G5543, "good/kind") is nearly homophonous with "Christos" (Χριστός)—a wordplay well known in the early church (cf. Tertullian). The "tasting" of the Lord\'s goodness typologically anticipates the Eucharistic experience and the believer\'s direct encounter with Christ.',
        4: 'THEOLOGICAL: "Lithon zōnta" (λίθον ζῶντα)—"a living stone"—is a striking paradox. Stones are inert; Christ as the Living Stone reverses this. The dual verdict is emphatic: "by men rejected" (apodedokimasmenon) versus "before God chosen and precious" (eklekton entimon). This sets up the extended stone-testimony catena in vv.6-8.',
        5: 'DIVINE_COUNCIL: Believers as "living stones" are built into a "spiritual house" (oikos pneumatikos) forming a "holy priesthood" (hierateuma hagion). This is a radical reconstitution of Israel\'s temple theology—the community of Christ replaces the Jerusalem temple as the locus of God\'s dwelling and sacrificial worship. The priestly role once reserved for Levites is now extended to the entire covenant people through Christ (cf. Exod 19:6; Rev 1:6).',
        6: 'TYPOLOGY: Peter quotes Isaiah 28:16 (LXX), identifying Christ as the cornerstone laid in Zion. "Akrogōniaion" (ἀκρογωνιαῖον, G204) refers to the chief corner-foundation stone that determines the alignment of the entire structure. The promise "shall by no means be put to shame" (ou mē kataischynthē) uses the emphatic double negative, guaranteeing the security of those who trust in the Messiah.',
        8: 'THEOLOGICAL: Peter weaves together Isaiah 8:14 and Psalm 118:22 to present Christ as both cornerstone and stumbling-stone. The phrase "unto which also they were appointed" (eis ho kai etethēsan) is theologically weighty, indicating that the stumbling of the disobedient falls within God\'s sovereign decree. The same stone that saves believers becomes the occasion of judgment for the disobedient.',
        9: 'STRUCTURE: This verse is a dense mosaic of Exodus 19:5-6 and Isaiah 43:20-21 (LXX). Four titles are applied to the church: "chosen race" (genos eklekton), "royal priesthood" (basileion hierateuma), "holy nation" (ethnos hagion), "people for possession" (laos eis peripoiēsin). DIVINE_COUNCIL: These titles, originally given to Israel at Sinai, are now applied to the multi-ethnic body of Christ, indicating a transfer of covenant vocation. "Aretas" (ἀρετάς, G703) means "excellencies" or "mighty deeds," not merely moral virtues—it refers to God\'s powerful acts of deliverance.',
        10: 'TYPOLOGY: Peter quotes Hosea 2:23 (LXX 2:25) and 1:6, 9. The prophet\'s children "Lo-Ammi" (Not My People) and "Lo-Ruhamah" (Not Shown Mercy) become types of the Gentile believers now grafted into God\'s covenant people. What was prophetic reversal in Hosea—the restoration of faithless Israel—Peter applies to the ingathering of the nations into the Messianic community (cf. Rom 9:25-26).',
        17: 'GREEK: Four staccato imperatives form a memorable ethical summary. "Pantas timēsate" (aorist—honor all as a decisive commitment), "tēn adelphotēta agapate" (present—continually love the brotherhood), "ton theon phobeisthe" (present—continually fear God), "ton basilea timate" (present—continually honor the king). The chiastic structure pairs universal honor with royal honor, and fraternal love with divine fear.',
        21: 'THEOLOGICAL: "Hypogrammon" (ὑπογραμμόν, G5261) appears only here in the NT—a writing-template or tracing pattern used by students learning to write. Christ\'s suffering is not merely exemplary but constitutive: "hyper hymōn" (on your behalf) indicates substitutionary purpose. Peter holds together the atoning and the exemplary dimensions of Christ\'s passion without collapsing one into the other.',
        24: 'TYPOLOGY: Peter draws heavily on Isaiah 53:4-5, 12 (LXX). "Bore our sins in his body upon the tree (xylon)"—"xylon" (ξύλον, G3586) echoes Deuteronomy 21:22-23, where hanging on a tree signifies bearing the covenant curse (cf. Gal 3:13). "Mōlōpi" (μώλωπι, G3468) is singular—"by his one wound"—emphasizing the singular, sufficient atoning act. The purpose clause "that having died to sins we might live to righteousness" captures the full transfer from the dominion of sin to the dominion of righteousness through Christ\'s substitutionary death.',
        25: 'TYPOLOGY: Peter quotes Isaiah 53:6 (LXX), completing the Suffering Servant passage. "Shepherd" (poimēn, G4166) and "Overseer" (episkopos, G1985) are applied to Christ, echoing Ezekiel 34:11-16 where God himself promises to shepherd his scattered flock. THEOLOGICAL: The pairing of these titles establishes Christ as both the tender caretaker and the authoritative guardian of souls, fulfilling the divine shepherd prophecy and grounding all later pastoral office in his person.',
    },
    3: {
        1: 'GREEK: "Hypotassómenai" (ὑποτασσόμεναι, Strong\'s G5293) is a middle/passive participle meaning "placing oneself under order." It is a military term denoting voluntary arrangement within a structure, not servile subjection. "Apeithéō" (G544) means specifically to disbelieve or be non-compliant, distinct from simple unbelief (apistéō). "Anastrophḗ" (G391) denotes one\'s entire manner of life or conduct, a key term Peter uses seven times in his epistles.',
        4: 'THEOLOGICAL: The "hidden person of the heart" (ho kryptòs tēs kardíasánthrōpos) parallels Paul\'s "inner man" (Rom 7:22; 2 Cor 4:16). "Áphthartos" (G862, imperishable/incorruptible) is the same word applied to God himself (Rom 1:23) and to the resurrection body (1 Cor 15:52), elevating the gentle spirit to an eternal quality. The combination of "praÿs" (gentle/meek) and "hēsýchios" (quiet/tranquil) echoes Christ\'s own self-description in Matt 11:29.',
        6: 'TYPOLOGY: Peter draws on Gen 18:12 (LXX) where Sarah refers to Abraham as "kýrios" (lord). Believers become Sarah\'s "children" (tékna) not by lineage but by imitation of faith—paralleling the Abrahamic faith-lineage argument of Gal 3:7. "Ptóēsis" (G4423) is a hapax legomenon in the NT, meaning a sudden terror or alarming disturbance, possibly drawn from Prov 3:25 (LXX).',
        7: 'THEOLOGICAL: "Synklēronómois cháritos zōēs" (fellow-heirs of the grace of life) places husband and wife in radical co-equal status before God regarding the inheritance of salvation, even within a structured household order. The warning that prayers may be "hindered" (enkóptō, G1581, lit. "cut into," a military term for breaking up a road) implies that domestic injustice directly impedes one\'s spiritual access to God.',
        9: 'STRUCTURE: This verse pivots from household codes (vv. 1-7) to the entire community. The call to "bless" (eulogéō) those who revile echoes Jesus\' teaching in Luke 6:28. "Klēronoméō" (G2816, to inherit) ties believers\' conduct to their eschatological inheritance—blessing is both the means and the end of the Christian calling.',
        12: 'TYPOLOGY: Peter quotes Psalm 34:12-16 (LXX Ps 33:13-17), a psalm of David when he feigned madness before Abimelech. The "face of the Lord" (prósōpon Kyríou) set "against" (epí) evildoers reflects the divine council judgment motif where God\'s direct gaze constitutes verdict. In the LXX, this psalm was associated with the righteous sufferer—a type Peter applies to persecuted believers.',
        15: 'THEOLOGICAL: "Kýrion dè tòn Christòn hagiásate" (sanctify the Lord Christ) is a deliberate adaptation of Isa 8:13 (LXX: "Kýrion autòn hagiásate"), where YHWH of hosts is the one to be sanctified. Peter applies this YHWH text directly to Christ, making an extraordinary identification of Jesus with the God of Israel. "Apología" (G627) is a legal term for a formal courtroom defense, indicating that the early church expected official interrogation regarding their faith.',
        18: 'THEOLOGICAL: "Hápax perì hamartiōn épathen" (once for sins he suffered) declares the unrepeatable, definitive nature of Christ\'s atoning work (cf. Heb 9:28, 10:10). The formula "díkaios hypèr adíkōn" (the righteous on behalf of the unrighteous) is substitutionary atonement in its most compressed form. The contrast "thanatotheìs mèn sarkí, zōopoietheìs dè pneúmati" (put to death in flesh, made alive in Spirit) marks the transition from Christ\'s mortal state to his resurrected, Spirit-empowered state.',
        19: 'DIVINE_COUNCIL: "Toîs en phylakē pneúmasin" (the spirits in prison) most likely refers to the imprisoned angelic beings of Gen 6:1-4, the "sons of God" (bene elohim) who transgressed their proper domain. This reading is supported by 2 Pet 2:4 and Jude 6, and aligns with 1 Enoch 10-16 where fallen Watchers are bound in chains awaiting judgment. Christ\'s proclamation (ekḗryxen, G2784, heralded as a victor) to these spirits is not a rescue mission but a declaration of triumph and authority over the rebellious divine council members.',
        20: 'HISTORICAL: The reference to Noah\'s ark and the eight souls (oktṓ psychaí) preserved "through water" (di\' hýdatos) connects the flood narrative of Gen 6-8 with the theme of God saving a faithful remnant through judgment. In Second Temple Judaism, the flood was understood as divine judgment upon the corruption caused by the Watchers (1 Enoch 6-11), directly linking this verse to the "spirits in prison" of v. 19. "Apekdéchomai" (G553) expresses God\'s patient, expectant waiting.',
        21: 'GREEK: "Antítypon" (G499) means "corresponding type" or "antitype"—the fulfillment that corresponds to an earlier figure (týpos). Peter declares baptism to be the antitype of the flood waters. "Eperṓtēma" (G1906) is a rare word, possibly meaning "pledge" or "appeal"—some scholars read it as a formal contractual commitment (as in legal papyri), others as a prayerful appeal. It is the conscience\'s active response toward God, not a mere ritual. The entire saving efficacy is grounded "through the resurrection of Jesus Christ" (di\' anastáseōs Iēsoû Christoû).',
        22: 'DIVINE_COUNCIL: Christ\'s session "at the right hand of God" fulfills Ps 110:1 and represents enthronement as cosmic King. "Angels and authorities and powers" (angélōn kaì exousiōn kaì dynámeōn) being "subjected" (hypotagéntōn, G5293) to him describes the entire spiritual hierarchy—both loyal and rebellious members of the divine council—placed under Christ\'s sovereign rule. This forms an inclusio with v. 19: the same Christ who proclaimed to imprisoned spirits now reigns over all heavenly powers (cf. Eph 1:20-22; Col 2:15; Phil 2:9-11).',
    },
    4: {
        1: 'GREEK: "ὁπλίσασθε" (hoplisasthe, from hoplízō, Strong\'s G3695) is a military term meaning "arm yourselves," used only here in the NT. The imperative middle voice implies personally taking up armor. The "mind" (énnoia, G1771) of Christ\'s suffering becomes the believer\'s weapon. THEOLOGICAL: The phrase "has ceased from sin" does not imply sinless perfection but a decisive break with sin\'s dominion through identification with Christ\'s suffering in the flesh.',
        3: 'GREEK: "οἰνοφλυγίαις" (oinophlygíais, G3632) is a NT hapax legomenon meaning "wine-bubbling," i.e., drunkenness to the point of overflow. The vice list represents a standard catalog of Gentile excess. HISTORICAL: These vices were characteristic of Greco-Roman pagan worship and social life, particularly associated with Dionysiac cult practices common in Asia Minor, where Peter\'s recipients lived (1 Pet 1:1).',
        6: 'THEOLOGICAL: This is one of the most debated verses in the NT. The "dead" (nekroîs) to whom the gospel was proclaimed likely refers to those who heard the gospel while alive but have since died, connecting to 3:18-20. The purpose clause establishes a contrast: judged in flesh (physical death, the human verdict) yet living in spirit (the divine reality). DIVINE_COUNCIL: The scope of Christ\'s proclamation extends beyond the living, asserting his sovereign lordship over all realms.',
        8: 'GREEK: "ἐκτενῆ" (ektenē, G1618) means "stretched out, fervent, intense"—the image is of a muscle straining at full extension. TYPOLOGY: "Love covers a multitude of sins" quotes Proverbs 10:12 (LXX), reinterpreted through the lens of Christ\'s atoning love. This is not concealment of evil but the redemptive power of sacrificial love within the community.',
        11: 'GREEK: "λόγια θεοῦ" (lógia theoû, "oracles of God") echoes the LXX usage for divine utterances (cf. Rom 3:2, Acts 7:38). "χορηγεῖ" (chorēgeî, G5524) originally meant to fund a chorus in Greek theater, hence "to supply generously." THEOLOGICAL: The doxology\'s attribution of glory and dominion "through Jesus Christ" to God—with the relative pronoun "to whom" (hō) grammatically capable of referring to Christ—affirms the inseparable glorification of Father and Son.',
        14: 'THEOLOGICAL: "The Spirit of glory and of God" (τὸ τῆς δόξης καὶ τὸ τοῦ θεοῦ πνεῦμα) describes the Holy Spirit as the very presence of divine glory resting (anapaúetai) upon the persecuted. TYPOLOGY: The language of the Spirit "resting upon" echoes Isaiah 11:2 (LXX), where the Spirit of the Lord rests upon the Messianic Branch, now extended to those who share in Christ\'s reproach (cf. Num 11:25-26).',
        17: 'TYPOLOGY: "Judgment begins from the house of God" echoes Ezekiel 9:6 (LXX), where divine judgment begins at the sanctuary. The believing community is now the temple/house of God (1 Pet 2:5). THEOLOGICAL: The argument moves from lesser to greater (a fortiori): if God\'s own household undergoes purifying judgment through suffering, the fate of those who reject the gospel is incomparably more severe.',
        18: 'GREEK: This verse quotes Proverbs 11:31 (LXX), not the Hebrew MT. "μόλις" (mólis, G3433) means "with difficulty, scarcely." TYPOLOGY: The LXX rendering intensifies the Hebrew original, emphasizing that salvation is not by human merit but by divine grace through arduous faithfulness, framing the believer\'s suffering as the narrow path of eschatological deliverance.',
        19: 'GREEK: "κτίστῃ" (ktístē, G2939) is a NT hapax legomenon, meaning "Creator." Peter deliberately chooses this title to ground trust in God\'s sovereign power over all creation. THEOLOGICAL: The commendation of souls to a "faithful Creator" echoes Christ\'s own words on the cross (Luke 23:46, quoting Ps 31:5). Suffering according to God\'s will is met not with passive resignation but active well-doing (agathopoiía), a key Petrine theme (cf. 1 Pet 2:15, 20; 3:6, 17).',
    },
    5: {
        1: 'GREEK: "Sympresbyteros" (συμπρεσβύτερος, Strong\'s G4850) is a rare compound meaning "fellow-elder," used only here in the NT — Peter places himself alongside local church leaders rather than asserting apostolic rank. "Martys" (μάρτυς) here means "witness" in its original sense, not yet the later technical meaning of one who dies for the faith, though Peter\'s eyewitness testimony would indeed lead to martyrdom. "Koinōnos" (κοινωνός) of the coming glory indicates Peter\'s certain share in eschatological reward (Rom 8:17).',
        2: 'GREEK: "Poimanate" (ποιμάνατε) is an aorist imperative of "poimainō" (Strong\'s G4165), meaning "shepherd" — echoing the risen Christ\'s command to Peter himself in John 21:16. "Episkopountes" (ἐπισκοποῦντες), "exercising oversight," is the verbal form from which "episkopos" (bishop/overseer) derives, showing that elder and overseer functions overlapped in the early church. TYPOLOGY: The shepherd imagery recalls God as Shepherd of Israel (Ps 23:1; Ezek 34:11-16), with Christ as the ultimate fulfillment and elders as under-shepherds.',
        4: 'GREEK: "Archipoimen" (ἀρχιποίμην, Strong\'s G750) is a NT hapax legomenon — "Chief Shepherd" — uniquely applied to Christ, distinguishing Him from all human under-shepherds. "Amarantinon" (ἀμαράντινον, Strong\'s G262), "unfading," also a hapax, formed from the amaranth flower that supposedly never withers, contrasts with the perishable wreaths of Greek athletic games. TYPOLOGY: The "crown of glory" (stephanos tēs doxēs) stands in contrast to the corruptible crowns of the age and recalls the eschatological reward motif (2 Tim 4:8; Jas 1:12; Rev 2:10).',
        5: 'THEOLOGICAL: The quotation is from Proverbs 3:34 LXX — "God opposes the proud, but gives grace to the humble" — also cited by James (Jas 4:6). GREEK: "Enkombōsasthe" (ἐγκομβώσασθε, Strong\'s G1463) is a NT hapax meaning "to tie on" or "to clothe oneself with," derived from "enkombōma," a slave\'s apron or work garment. This striking image may evoke Christ girding Himself with a towel to wash the disciples\' feet (John 13:4-5). DIVINE_COUNCIL: God\'s opposition to the proud echoes the cosmic pattern of divine resistance to the arrogant — both human and heavenly powers who exalt themselves (Isa 14:12-15; Ezek 28:2-7).',
        8: 'THEOLOGICAL: The devil (diábolos, "slanderer/accuser") is depicted in his cosmic role as adversary (antídikos, a legal term for an opponent in court), evoking the accuser of Job 1:6-12 and Zechariah 3:1. DIVINE_COUNCIL: This verse reflects the Second Temple understanding of a hostile spiritual being who roams creation seeking to destroy the faithful. The lion imagery echoes Psalm 22:13 and the predatory threat of hostile spiritual powers against God\'s people. The sober vigilance commanded implies spiritual warfare awareness (Eph 6:11-12).',
        10: 'GREEK: Peter employs four powerful verbs in sequence: "katartisei" (καταρτίσει, restore/make complete), "stērixei" (στηρίξει, establish firmly), "sthenōsei" (σθενώσει, strengthen — a NT hapax, Strong\'s G4599), and "themeliōsei" (θεμελιώσει, lay a foundation). This fourfold promise assures comprehensive divine restoration after suffering. THEOLOGICAL: The title "God of all grace" encapsulates the letter\'s central theme — that divine grace undergirds believers through persecution. The calling into "eternal glory in Christ" frames all present suffering as temporary against an eschatological horizon of unending splendor (2 Cor 4:17).',
        13: 'HISTORICAL: "She who is in Babylon, chosen together with you" most likely refers to the church in Rome, with "Babylon" functioning as a cryptic designation for Rome — a convention well attested in Jewish apocalyptic literature (Rev 17:5; 2 Baruch 11:1; Sib. Or. 5.143). Mark is traditionally identified as John Mark (Acts 12:12, 25), and "my son" indicates a spiritual father-son relationship. This co-location of Peter and Mark in Rome accords with early tradition that Mark composed his Gospel from Peter\'s testimony (Papias via Eusebius, Hist. Eccl. 3.39.15).',
    },
}